<h1>GCC Cross Compiler</h1>
<p>
This information applies to cross compiling with GCC targeting user mode Linux/Unix or a
<a href=env_custom.html>custom environment</a>.

<h2>Build Run-Time Library</h2>
<p>
Use commands like those shown below to build the BullseyeCoverage run-time library.
Modify the compile command to use the same compiler options as your project.
These commands are for a Bourne-compatible shell such as bash.
<pre>
cd <i>BullseyeCoverage</i>/run
cc=arm-linux-gcc    # customize to your tool chain
ar=arm-linux-ar     # customize to your tool chain

src=libcov-posix.c  # for Linux/Unix
#src=libcov-user.c  # for custom environment

$cc -c -D_REENTRANT -fPIC -O2 -o libcov-cross.o $src
$ar -rc ../lib/libcov-`$cc -dumpmachine`.a libcov-cross.o
</pre>

<h2>Build Project</h2>
<p>
Make sure the <i>BullseyeCoverage</i><code>/bin</code> is first in the <code>PATH</code> environment variable.
Enable Coverage Build and build your project object files.
For example:
<pre>
export PATH=/opt/BullseyeCoverage/bin:$PATH
cov01 -1
make
</pre>

<h2>Running on Linux/Unix</h2>
<p>
Before running your test program,
set environment variable <code>COVFILE</code> on the target device to the path of your coverage file
located on your host system.
You must have read and write access to the coverage file.
For example:
<pre>
$ export COVFILE=/host/project/test.cov
$ ./a.out
</pre>

